      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the goblins are just a bit too eager to eat the gold coins! You are absolutely right to want to stop the manual deallocation headache. In C++, the smart pointers are the goblins who have learned to be polite and leave the gold coins exactly where they belong.\n\nFor your specific case of a trading engine processing orders, **`std::unique_ptr<Order>`** is the correct choice.\n\nHere is why:\n1.  **Ownership:** `unique_ptr` means only *one* owner exists at a time. If you pass a `unique_ptr` to `executeTrade`, that function owns the Order. Once the function returns, the goblin (the `unique_ptr`) automatically releases the gold, and the heap is clean.\n2.  **No Shared Ownership:** You don't want multiple threads or parts of your engine sharing the same Order object, which could lead to race conditions or memory leaks if the goblins get confused about who owns what.\n\nHere is the refactored code using `std::unique_ptr`:\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory> // For std::unique_ptr\n\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> ord) {\n    if (ord->isValid())",
